# The Bootstrap Rules

Every language has to start somewhere. Incant starts with 32 rules hard-coded in C++.

That's the bootstrap problem: you need a language to define a language. Incant solves it by
hard-coding the smallest possible set of rules — just enough to define what a field is and
how fields are written. Once those 32 rules exist, incant can read a setup file written in
its own syntax and define everything else from there.

This page walks through those 32 rules: what each one does, and how they fit together into
something that can define itself.

---

## What They Do

The bootstrap rules fall into four natural groups. It helps to see the groups before
looking at the rules one by one.

**Character matchers** — the smallest building blocks. Rules that recognize a digit, a
letter, a quote character, a modifier symbol. Everything else is built from these.

**Literal matchers** — rules that recognize specific pieces of incant syntax: numbers,
names, quoted strings, code blocks, character sets.

**Structure rules** — rules that recognize the *shape* of an incant definition: a trait
(name plus optional data), a set of attributes, a set of members, the full definition
itself.

**Housekeeping rules** — rules that handle the mechanics of running incant: invoking a
rule by name, running a sequence of rules at startup, turning on debug output.

Here is the full list, grouped that way:

```
// Character matchers
counter=[0-9];
modifySet=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$];
nameSet=[a-zA-Z0-9];

// Literal matchers
PoweR=[eE] sign?=[+-] power=[0-9]+;
FloaT="." decimals=[0-9]+ PoweR?;
tokenize^@;
NumbeR=numberSet=[0-9]+ FloaT? tokenize;
QuotE               tik=['"] quoteBody}=tik$@;
NamE                first-=[a-zA-Z] nameSet-^* tokenize;
GrouP
    NamE;
    QuotE;
CodE                "{" "}" parseAction;
DatA
    GrouP;
    NumbeR;
    CodE;
    SetBrackets     '['- ']'};
    NotA=[^ \t\r\n;]+;

// Structure rules
Modifier=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$] noPrint;
TraiTdata           '='- DatA Modifier* Limit?;
TraiT               NamE Modifier* Limit? TraiTdata?;
Attributes=TraiT+;
Limit               '['- min=[0-9]+ max?=[0-9]+ ']'- noPrint;
MemberS             ':'- Mlist=DefinE+;
NewGroup            TraiT@;
DefinE;
DefinE              NewGroup Attributes? MemberS endDefine-=[;>];

// Housekeeping
debug               "ALL"? "GUARD"? rules=NamE* ';'-;
InvokE              '('- NamE? ')'-;
define              DEFINing- definitions=DefinE+ DEFINing- ';'-;
RunRulE             NamE InvokE? ';'-?;
InitiatE=RunRulE+;
```

---

## How They Work

### The character matchers

```
counter=[0-9];
modifySet=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$];
nameSet=[a-zA-Z0-9];
```

These three rules each match a single character from a set. The `[...]` syntax is a
character set — same idea as a regular expression character class.

`counter` matches any digit. `nameSet` matches any letter or digit. `modifySet` matches
any of the special symbols that act as modifier characters in incant syntax — the `?`, `+`,
`*`, `@`, `^`, `}`, and others that you will see attached to rules throughout the bootstrap
list.

They don't do anything on their own. They exist so other rules can reference them.

---

### Building a number

```
PoweR=[eE] sign?=[+-] power=[0-9]+;
FloaT="." decimals=[0-9]+ PoweR?;
tokenize^@;
NumbeR=numberSet=[0-9]+ FloaT? tokenize;
```

`PoweR` matches a scientific notation exponent: the letter `e` or `E`, an optional sign,
and one or more digits. The `?` on `sign` means optional.

`FloaT` matches a decimal fraction: a literal dot, one or more digits, and an optional
exponent.

`NumbeR` matches a complete number: one or more digits, an optional `FloaT`, and then
`tokenize`. The `=` prefix on `NumbeR` means the whole match is stored as a single data
value rather than broken into sub-fields.

`tokenize` is unusual — it has no parsing definition of its own. The `^@` means its
behavior is a hard-coded C++ method. When `NumbeR` finishes matching digits and an
optional decimal, `tokenize` fires and converts the raw matched text into an actual
numeric value. It's the bridge between "characters that look like a number" and "a number."

---

### Names and quoted strings

```
QuotE               tik=['"] quoteBody}=tik$@;
NamE                first-=[a-zA-Z] nameSet-^* tokenize;
```

`QuotE` matches a quoted string. It captures the opening quote character (either `'` or
`"`) into `tik`, then matches everything up to the matching closing quote. The `}=tik`
means "match until you see the character stored in `tik`." The `$@` means the result is
handled by a C++ method. So `QuotE` can handle both `'single quoted'` and `"double
quoted"` strings using the same rule — it remembers which quote it opened with and
matches until it sees the same one.

`NamE` matches an identifier. It requires a letter first (`first-=[a-zA-Z]`), followed by
zero or more letters or digits (`nameSet-^*`). The `-` modifier means these sub-matches
are consumed but not stored as separate fields — only the whole name matters. `tokenize`
fires at the end to finalize the name as a value.

---

### Groups, code blocks, and data

```
GrouP
    NamE;
    QuotE;

CodE                "{" "}" parseAction;

DatA
    GrouP;
    NumbeR;
    CodE;
    SetBrackets     '['- ']'};
    NotA=[^ \t\r\n;]+;
```

`GrouP` is an *options rule* — it tries `NamE` first, then `QuotE`. The indented list
without colons is incant's way of writing alternatives: try each one in order until one
succeeds. A group is either a name or a quoted string.

`CodE` matches a `{ ... }` block. The `parseAction` at the end is a hard-coded C++ method
that processes the block's contents as incant code. This is how action bodies get
attached to rules.

`DatA` is the most general data matcher — it tries five alternatives in order: a `GrouP`
(name or quoted string), a `NumbeR`, a `CodE` block, a `SetBrackets` character set
(`[...]`), or a `NotA` — anything that isn't whitespace or a semicolon. `DatA` is the
rule that answers "what kind of value can a field hold?" The answer is: any of these five
things.

---

### The structure rules — how a definition is built

This is where the bootstrap closes on itself. These rules define what an incant field
definition looks like — and they are themselves field definitions.

```
Modifier=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$] noPrint;
TraiTdata           '='- DatA Modifier* Limit?;
TraiT               NamE Modifier* Limit? TraiTdata?;
Attributes=TraiT+;
Limit               '['- min=[0-9]+ max?=[0-9]+ ']'- noPrint;
MemberS             ':'- Mlist=DefinE+;
NewGroup            TraiT@;
```

A `Modifier` is one of the special symbols — `?`, `+`, `*`, `@`, `^`, `}`, and others.
`noPrint` means the modifier character itself is not included in the result; only its
effect matters.

A `TraiT` is a name optionally followed by modifiers, an optional repeat `Limit`, and
optional `TraiTdata` (which is an `=` sign followed by a value). A trait is the basic
unit of a field definition — a name, its behavior flags, and optionally its data.

`Attributes` is one or more traits. When you write something like:

```
person name="Anthony" age=42;
```

`name="Anthony"` and `age=42` are both traits. Together they are the attributes of the
`person` field.

`Limit` matches a `[min max]` repeat constraint — the `[0-9]+` in many rules above is
shorthand for "one or more," which is a limit with min=1.

`MemberS` matches the member list of a field — a colon followed by one or more `DefinE`
rules. This is where fields nest: a field's members are themselves full field definitions.

`NewGroup` matches the opening trait of a definition with the `@` modifier, which means
"store the whole matched result here."

---

### DefinE — the rule that defines all rules

```
DefinE;
DefinE              NewGroup Attributes? MemberS endDefine-=[;>];
```

`DefinE` appears twice. The first line is a forward declaration — a bare name with
nothing but a semicolon. It says: this rule exists. Trust me. Details to follow.

This is necessary because `MemberS` references `DefinE` (a member list is a list of
`DefinE` rules), and `DefinE` references `MemberS`. Each one needs the other. The forward
declaration breaks the chicken-and-egg problem the same way a C++ forward declaration
does — no special keyword needed, just a placeholder with the same shape as the real
thing.

The second `DefinE` is the full definition. A complete field definition consists of:

- A `NewGroup` — the name and opening trait
- Optional `Attributes` — zero or more name=value pairs
- Optional `MemberS` — a nested member list
- `endDefine` — which matches either `;` or `>` to close the definition

`endDefine` with the `-` modifier means the closing character is consumed but not stored.
`=[;>]` means it accepts either a semicolon or a `>` as the terminator.

This single rule — `DefinE` — is what allows everything in incant to be defined in incant
syntax. When you write `person name="Anthony" age=42;`, `DefinE` is the rule that
recognizes and processes it.

---

### DEFINing and clean indentation

```
define              DEFINing- definitions=DefinE+ DEFINing- ';'-;
```

The `define` rule wraps a block of `DefinE` rules. The `DEFINing` on each side is a
command that sets a flag in the runtime. That flag tells the pretty-printer it is inside a
definition block, which is how incant definitions get their clean Python-like indentation.
The language cares about how it looks — not as an afterthought, but baked into the parsing
machinery from the start.

---

### The housekeeping rules

```
debug               "ALL"? "GUARD"? rules=NamE* ';'-;
InvokE              '('- NamE? ')'-;
RunRulE             NamE InvokE? ';'-?;
InitiatE=RunRulE+;
```

`debug` turns on diagnostic output — optionally for all rules, optionally with guard
tracing, optionally for named rules only.

`InvokE` matches the `(name)` call syntax used when invoking a rule as a method.

`RunRulE` matches a single rule invocation: a name, an optional `InvokE`, and an optional
semicolon. It's how incant runs things.

`InitiatE` is one or more `RunRulE` invocations. It's the entry point — the rule that
reads and executes the startup sequence when incant launches.

---

## The Payoff

Thirty-two rules. Most of them fit on one line. Together they define:

- What a character set looks like
- What a number looks like
- What a name looks like
- What a quoted string looks like
- What a field definition looks like
- What a member list looks like
- How to run things at startup

From these 32, incant loads its setup file — which is written in incant syntax, read by
these same rules — and defines the rest of the language. Then programs written in that
language can define new rules. Those rules can define new languages. The field that
started as a comma matcher ends up, several layers of definition later, as a distributed
messaging primitive or a cloud-hosted AI.

That's what it means for a language to define itself. The 32 rules are not clever. They
are the minimum. Everything clever comes after.
